5. Environment Configuration Framework

Objective

Provide environment-specific configuration independent of runtime host selection.

Configuration Hierarchy

group_vars/
|
├── all.yml
├── platform.yml
├── dev.yml
├── qa.yml
├── uat.yml
└── prod.yml

---

all.yml

Contains framework-wide defaults.

Examples:

- timeout settings
- retry settings
- reporting defaults
- checkpoint defaults

---

platform.yml

Contains organization-level settings.

Examples:

- Artifactory base URL
- SMTP settings
- AWX metadata

---

Environment Files

Contain environment-specific values.

Examples:

- deployment roots
- report locations
- notification recipients
- allowed runtime users

---

6. Runtime Host Selection Framework

Objective

Allow execution host selection at workflow launch.

Input

{
  "environment": "QA",
  "targetHost": "qa-host-01"
}

Validation

The framework shall validate:

- Host format
- Host accessibility
- Runtime user permissions

Result

The validated host becomes the execution target for all artifact activities.

---

7. Manifest Framework

Objective

Provide a structured contract for execution requests.

The manifest contains:

- Environment
- Execution mode
- Runtime host
- Artifact list
- Notification settings
- Resume settings

Validation

Validation checks include:

- Required field validation
- Schema validation
- Execution mode validation
- Artifact definition validation

Invalid manifests shall terminate execution.

---

8. Artifact Metadata Framework

Objective

Standardize onboarding of new artifacts.

Metadata defines:

- Deployment requirements
- Execution commands
- Validation strategy
- Reporting configuration

Example:

artifact_name: payment-service

deployment_required: true

execution_command: ./run_regression.sh

validation_script: compare_results.sh

---

9. Artifact Lifecycle Framework

Each artifact follows the same lifecycle.

Cleanup
  |
Precheck
  |
Deploy
  |
Sanity
  |
Execute
  |
Validation
  |
Housekeeping

---

Cleanup

Removes previous execution artifacts.

---

Precheck

Validates prerequisites.

Examples:

- disk space
- file availability
- permissions

---

Deploy

Downloads and deploys artifacts.

---

Sanity

Validates successful deployment.

---

Execute

Runs artifact-specific execution commands.

---

Validation

Compares outputs.

Generates validation results.

---

Housekeeping

Archives temporary files.

---

10. Parallel Execution Framework

Objective

Support concurrent execution of multiple artifacts.

Constraints

Maximum concurrent artifacts:

5

---

Execution Model

Artifact A
Artifact B
Artifact C
Artifact D
Artifact E

execute simultaneously on the selected runtime host.

---

Isolation Requirements

Each artifact shall have:

- Dedicated workspace
- Dedicated report directory
- Dedicated checkpoint directory

---

Failure Handling

Failure of one artifact shall not terminate other artifact executions.

---

11. Sequential Execution Framework

Objective

Support ordered artifact execution.

Model

Artifact A
   |
Artifact B
   |
Artifact C

Each artifact begins only after successful completion of the previous artifact.

---

12. Timeout Supervision Framework

Objective

Prevent hung executions.

Controls

Artifact-level timeout.

Example:

artifact_timeout_minutes: 120

Behavior

When timeout occurs:

- Process terminated
- Artifact marked failed
- Failure reported

---

13. Validation Framework

Objective

Determine regression success.

Validation strategies:

- File comparison
- Script-based comparison
- Custom validation logic

Output:

{
  "artifact": "payment-service",
  "status": "FAILED",
  "difference_count": 12
}

